<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-446-130  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 446 130.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  July 1989 v12 n7 p88(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Exotic CAD: given what's happening in R andamp; D, tomorrow's CAD systemmay be something you wear. (computer aided design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Orr, Joel N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer aided design technology is moving from the typical twodimensional, complex systems to futuristic technologies such asstereolithography and laser sintering.andP;  Many of these technologiesare still out of the reach of most designers.andP;  Emergingtechnologies are being developed for very complex aerospace andscientific laboratories that can make the investment in hardwareand software.andP;  However, some new technologies will ultimately letdesigners make three-dimensional representations that can bedisplayed, touched, and manipulated.andP;  A lower-end, currenttechnology is offered in a Showcase Systems draft station thatuses a display that is projected on a full-size drafting table.andO;However, the larger size does not add to the resolution of thegraphics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignGraphics SystemsResearch and DevelopmentTechnologyStereolithographyLasersUser Needs.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>